<h3>
    <strong>1. Sandy River</strong> (flows past Gresham)
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Winter runs</strong>: peak <strong>late December–February</strong>, excellent hatchery returns (often 1,000+ fish) 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Summer runs</strong>: <strong>May–July</strong>, with a mix of hatchery and wild steelhead .
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Access</strong>: Oxbow Regional Park, Dodge Park, Lewis &amp; Clark Park, Cedar Creek mouth, Revenue Bridge 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Tactics</strong>: drift fishing, intruder flies, bobbers with yarnies or roe&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>2. Clackamas River</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Winter steelhead</strong>: peak <strong>January–March</strong>; robust hatchery returns 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Summer steelhead</strong>: <strong>May–August</strong>, smaller but catchable runs 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Top access spots</strong>:
        <ul>
            <li>
                <strong>Carver Park</strong>, <strong>High Rocks</strong>, <strong>Riverside Park</strong>, <strong>McIver Park</strong>, <strong>Barton Park</strong>, <strong>Eagle Creek mouth</strong>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Tactics</strong>: plunk plugs (Spin‑N‑Glos), drift fishing, bobber with cured roe&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>3. Willamette River (Lower, near Gladstone)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Winter steelhead</strong>: congregate at tentpoles like Meldrum Bar 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Access</strong>: Meldrum Bar Park, other parks below Willamette Falls 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Tactics</strong>: shore plunking with Spin‑N‑Glos .
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>4. Columbia River (Lower Gorge Area)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Summer steelhead</strong>: present <strong>May–August</strong>, often alongside spring Chinook 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Winter steelhead</strong>: less prominent, though winter steelhead show up .
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Access</strong>: Sauvie Island, Reeder Road, Government Island, Lower Gorge banks 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Tactics</strong>: plunking spinners and spoons on sandy beaches&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>5. Coastal &amp; Tributary Options (Day Trips)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Wilson River</strong>: ~1.5 hours west; <strong>winter steelhead year-round</strong>, excellent bank access along Hwy 6
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Nestucca River</strong>: coastal gem; both <strong>winter</strong> (wild, 10–12 lb avg) and <strong>summer steelhead</strong>, boat access in lower river
    </li>
</ul>
